6. PTY
The Linux Programming Interface" Chapter 64 (PTYs)

-Build a PTY wrapper only (no display)
-Study linenoise library - understand line editing
-Display & ANSI Build cell buffer
-Parse BASIC ANSI: \033[2J (clear), \033[H (cursor home)
-Parse BASIC ANSI: \033[2J (clear), \033[H (cursor home)
-Input & Vi Mode Raw terminal input
-Vi mode state machine
-Copy to clipboard integration
- Put it all together
- Add colors, basic graphics
- Bug fixes & testing

myterm/
├── src/
│   ├── pty.c           # PTY handling
│   ├── buffer.c        # Cell buffer
│   ├── ansi.c          # ANSI parser
│   ├── input.c         # Keyboard input
│   ├── vimode.c        # Vi mode
│   └── main.c          # Main loop
├── include/
│   └── term.h
├── Makefile
└── README.md

Project 1: PTY Cat (Day 1)
// Just forward between stdin and PTY
// 50 lines max, proves you understand PTY

Project 2: ANSI Viewer (Day 3)
// Read a file with ANSI codes, display it
// Tests your ANSI parser

Project 3: Screen Editor (Day 7)
// Full-screen text editor (like nano)
// Tests cell buffer and input

Project 4: Vi Mode Tester (Day 14)
// Just vi-mode selection on static text
// Isolate vi logic

Project 5: FINAL Terminal (Day 21+)
// Combine all above

Tools You Need
# Debugging tools
strace -e trace=read,write,ioctl ./myterm
hexdump -C  # See escape sequences
infocmp xterm-256color  # Terminal capabilities

# Development
gdb -tui ./myterm  # Debug with TUI
valgrind ./myterm  # Memory leaks

GOALS:
Can explain what a PTY is
Can set terminal to raw mode
Can parse \033[2J
Can implement circular buffer
Can handle resize signals
Can copy text to clipboard
Can implement vi visual mode

What terminal do:
Read from keyboard → write to PTY
Read from PTY → parse ANSI → update buffer → render
Handle signals (resize, interrupt)
